<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25106a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25106a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25106a"> 106(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> matter of little britain</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Wace, according to Layamon, dedicated his poem, which was completed in 1155, to &ldquo;the noble Eleanor, who was the high King Henry&apos;s queen.&rdquo; This statement&mdash;and there is no reason to doubt its truth&mdash;affords another indication of the interest of the Angevin court in the literary exploitation of &ldquo;<mark>the matter of Britain</mark>.&rdquo; Geoffrey had already besought royal approval for his presentment of British legends, and had done his best to clothe his account of Arthur&apos;s deeds in the highly-coloured rhetorical trappings that would commend it to courtly Norman readers. <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA2"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 89f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n53094g" href="n53all.htm#n53094g">N53 (VI.B.46):094(g)</a> and <a name="n56198d" href="n56all.htm#n56198d">N56 (VI.B.41):198(d)</a>. The &ldquo;Matter of Britain&rdquo; is the body of Medieval literature and legendary material associated with Great Britain, and sometimes Brittany (Little Britain, or Armorica), and the legendary kings and heroes associated with it, particularly King Arthur.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14064n" href="c14all.htm#c14064n">VI.C.14:064(n)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
